04582nam a22007815i 9780824837549DE-B159720210729020517.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210729t20092009hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248375497 a10.1515/97808248375492doi  a(DE-B1597)483860  a(OCoLC)671821515  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 4aPL984.E8bR44 2009eb 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a895.7/1422204aThe Red Room :bStories of Trauma in Contemporary Korea. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (200 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aModern Korean Fiction00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- t1. In the Realm of the Buddha -- tSpirit on the Wind -- tThe Red Room -- tAfterword :Trauma in Contemporary Korean Fiction0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aModern Korean fiction is to a large extent a literature of witness to the historic upheavals of twentieth-century Korea. Often inspired by their own experiences, contemporary writers continue to show us how individual Koreans have been traumatized by wartime violence—whether the uprooting of whole families from the ancestral home, life on the road as war refugees, or the violent deaths of loved ones. The Red Room brings together stories by three canonical Korean writers who examine trauma as a simple fact of life. In Pak Wan-so’s "In the Realm of the Buddha," trauma manifests itself as an undigested lump inside the narrator, a mass needing to be purged before it consumes her. The protagonist of O Chong-hui’s "Spirit on the Wind" suffers from an incomprehensible wanderlust—the result of trauma that has escaped her conscious memory. In the title story by Im Ch’or-u, trauma is recycled from torturer to victim when a teacher is arbitrarily detained by unnamed officials. Western readers may find these stories bleak, even chilling, yet they offer restorative truths when viewed in light of the suffering experienced by all victims of war and political violence regardless of place and time.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aKorean fictiony20th centuryxTranslations into English. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh1 aChôn-Húi, O, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCh’ôr-U, Im, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCumings, Bruce, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFulton, Bruce, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFulton, Bruce.1 aFulton, Ju-Chan.1 aWan-Sõ, Pak, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUHP eBook Package 2000-2013z978311056414308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Hawaii Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311066325940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082483754940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824837549423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780824837549.jpg  a978-3-11-056414-3  UHP eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagec2000d2014  a978-3-11-066325-9  University of Hawaii Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK